# 🔗 NanoURL — Complete Interview Study Guide

> **Project Name:** NanoURL (URL Shortener SaaS)
> **Stack:** Node.js · Express · PostgreSQL · Redis · BullMQ · Razorpay · Docker
> **GitHub:** `theNahraf/URL-Shortner`

---

## 1. 🗂️ What Is This Project?

NanoURL is a **production-grade, SaaS URL Shortener** — similar to Bitly or TinyURL — but built from scratch with full understanding of the internals. It converts long URLs like `https://example.com/very-long-path?with=params` into short ones like `nanourl.io/aB3xY`.

### Core Features
| Feature | Description |
|---|---|
| URL Shortening | Generate a unique 5-char code for any URL |
| Custom Aliases | Pro users can pick their own short code (`/mylink`) |
| Password Protection | Protect links behind a password |
| Expiry Dates | Links that auto-expire after a set time |
| One-Time Links | Link deactivates after first click |
| Click Analytics | Track clicks by country, browser, device, referrer |
| Time-Series Charts | Daily/weekly/hourly click trends |
| QR Code Generation | Generate QR codes for any link |
| User Auth | JWT-based signup, login, refresh token |
| Plans & Billing | Free / Pro / Business tiers via Razorpay subscriptions |
| Rate Limiting | Redis Token Bucket limiter per plan tier |
| Swagger API Docs | Auto-generated at `/api-docs` |
| Domain Blacklist | Block malicious/phishing URLs |
| Docker Support | Full dev stack in docker-compose |

---

## 2. 🧱 Technology Stack — What I Used & WHY

### Node.js + Express
- **Why Node?** Event-loop driven, non-blocking I/O is perfect for high-throughput redirect operations. URL shorteners are I/O bound (DB reads, cache lookups), not CPU bound.
- **Why Express?** Minimal, unopinionated. Gives full control over routing, middleware order, and error handling. No magic like NestJS.

### PostgreSQL (via Knex.js query builder)
- **Why PostgreSQL?** ACID transactions, strong indexing, `date_trunc` for time-series analytics, `inet` type for IP storage, `gen_random_uuid()` built-in.
- **Why not MySQL?** PostgreSQL has better analytical query support (`date_trunc`, window functions) needed for click analytics.
- **Why Knex.js?** Gives raw SQL power with a JS-friendly API. Has migrations built-in. More control than Sequelize ORM.
- **Connection Pool:** min=2, max=10 (dev) / max=20 (prod) to handle concurrent requests efficiently.

### Redis (via ioredis)
- **Why Redis?** Sub-millisecond lookups. A URL redirect should happen in <5ms — you can't afford a DB hit every time.
- **Usage 1 — Cache:** Short codes cached for 1 hour (`url:<shortCode>` → `longUrl`)
- **Usage 2 — Rate Limiting:** Token bucket stored as Redis hash per user/IP
- **Usage 3 — Blacklist:** Malicious domains stored in a Redis Set for O(1) lookup
- **Usage 4 — BullMQ:** Analytics jobs queued through Redis
- **Why ioredis?** Better performance and cluster support than the `redis` npm package.

### BullMQ (Job Queue)
- **Why a job queue?** Analytics (GeoIP lookup, DB insert) should NOT block the redirect. A user clicks → they get redirected in ~2ms → analytics written asynchronously.
- **Why BullMQ?** Built for Redis, supports retries with exponential backoff, concurrency control, job TTL. Production-ready.
- **Retry Policy:** 3 attempts with exponential backoff (1s, 2s, 4s).

### JWT (jsonwebtoken)
- **Why JWT?** Stateless — no server-side session storage needed. Scales horizontally. Access token (15 min) + Refresh token (7 days) pattern.
- **Why two tokens?** Access token is short-lived for security. Refresh token gives users seamless experience without logging in every 15 minutes.
- **Token storage:** Sent in cookies AND supported in `Authorization: Bearer` header (works for both browser clients and API clients).

### bcrypt
- **Why bcrypt?** Adaptive hashing — the cost factor makes it intentionally slow to brute-force. SALT_ROUNDS = 12 means ~400ms to hash — acceptable for login but costly for attackers.
- **Used for:** Password hashing (users) AND link password hashing.

### Razorpay
- **Why Razorpay?** Indian payment gateway, supports recurring subscriptions natively, no card required for test mode, excellent webhook support.
- **How it works:** Create subscription → Razorpay charges user monthly → Webhook fires → DB updated with new plan.
- **Webhook security:** HMAC-SHA256 signature verification to prevent fake events.

### Helmet
- **Why?** Sets critical HTTP security headers (CSP, HSTS, X-Frame-Options, XSS-Protection). One middleware, 10+ security wins.

### Compression
- **Why?** gzip/brotli compress API responses. Especially useful for analytics responses that may have large JSON data.

### Morgan
- **Why?** HTTP request logging. `dev` format in development (colored), `combined` (Apache-standard) in production for log aggregation tools.

### geoip-lite
- **Why?** Offline GeoIP lookup — no external API call, no latency, no cost. The IP-to-country mapping is bundled in the package.
- **Trade-off:** Less accurate than MaxMind paid API, but good enough for analytics.

### ua-parser-js
- **Why?** Parse User-Agent strings to extract browser, OS, device type. Used in the analytics worker to categorize clicks.

### qrcode
- **Why?** QR code generation for links. Output as base64 PNG, returned via API. No external service needed.

### Docker + Docker Compose
- **Why Docker?** Reproducible local environment. `docker-compose up` spins up PostgreSQL + Redis instantly.
- **Redis config:** `appendonly yes` (persistent), `maxmemory 256mb`, `allkeys-lru` eviction policy.

### Swagger (swagger-jsdoc + swagger-ui-express)
- **Why?** Auto-generated API documentation from JSDoc comments in route files. Always in sync with code.

