## 4. 🔬 Low-Level Design (LLD)

### 4.1 URL Shortening Flow (POST /api/shorten)

```
Client Request
     │
     ▼
optionalAuth (attach user if JWT present)
     │
     ▼
createRateLimiter('shorten') — Redis Token Bucket check
     │
     ▼
validate(url required) — express middleware
     │
     ▼
urlController.shortenUrl()
     │
     ├── validateUrl(longUrl)
     │     ├── validator.isURL() — must be http/https
     │     ├── max 2048 chars check
     │     ├── suspicious pattern check (.exe, javascript:, data:)
     │     └── re-shortening check (bit.ly etc blocked)
     │
     ├── isBlacklisted(longUrl) — Redis SISMEMBER O(1)
     │
     ├── Check plan limits (free: 100 links/month max)
     │
     ├── If customAlias:
     │     ├── Validate format [a-zA-Z0-9_-] 3-30 chars
     │     ├── Requires Pro+ plan
     │     └── Check uniqueness in DB
     │
     ├── Else: Generate shortCode
     │     └── crypto.randomBytes(5) → Base62 mapping
     │         Until unique (DB check loop)
     │
     ├── If password: bcrypt.hash(password, 10)
     │
     ├── DB INSERT into urls table
     │
     ├── Redis SET url:<shortCode> longUrl (EX 3600)
     │
     └── Increment user.links_created_this_month
```

---

### 4.2 URL Redirect Flow (GET /:shortCode)

```
GET /aB3xY
     │
     ▼
optionalAuth — attach user if logged in (for rate limit tier)
     │
     ▼
createRateLimiter('redirect') — different limits per tier
     │
     ▼
urlController.redirectUrl()
     │
     ▼
resolveUrl('aB3xY', requestMeta)
     │
     ├── Redis GET url:aB3xY
     │     ├── HIT: get longUrl from cache (~0.1ms)
     │     │   └── Still fetch DB record for metadata check
     │     └── MISS: DB SELECT WHERE short_code = 'aB3xY'
     │               └── Cache the result for next time
     │
     ├── Check is_active → 404 if false
     │
     ├── Check expires_at → 410 Gone if expired
     │     └── Also del from Redis cache
     │
     ├── Check password_hash
     │     └── bcrypt.compare(provided, hash)
     │
     ├── One-time link: set is_active=false, del Redis cache
     │
     ├── Increment click_count (inline DB update)
     │
     ├── Queue analytics job to BullMQ (async, non-blocking)
     │     Data: { urlId, ip, userAgent, referer, timestamp }
     │
     └── res.redirect(301|302, longUrl)
                  │
                  ▼
         Analytics Worker picks up job:
           • ua-parser-js → browser, device, OS
           • geoip-lite → country, city
           • DB INSERT into analytics table
```

**Why 301 vs 302?**
- Regular links → **301 Permanent** (browser caches, reduces future server load)
- One-time links → **302 Temporary** (browser should NOT cache, each click must hit server)

---

### 4.3 Rate Limiting — Token Bucket Algorithm (LLD)

The rate limiter uses a **Token Bucket** algorithm, implemented atomically in Redis using a **Lua script**.

**Why Lua?** Lua scripts run atomically in Redis — no race conditions between the READ-MODIFY-WRITE operations.

```lua
-- Lua script (runs atomically in Redis)
HMGET key → get current tokens, last_refill_time
elapsed = now - last_refill
refill = floor(elapsed / 1000 * max_tokens / interval)
tokens = min(max_tokens, tokens + refill)
IF tokens > 0:
  tokens -= 1
  allowed = 1
HMSET key tokens last_refill
EXPIRE key interval*2
RETURN [allowed, tokens, reset_in]
```

**Rate Limit Tiers:**
| Tier | Shorten | Redirect | Analytics | General |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Unauthenticated | 5/min | 50/min | 5/min | 30/min |
| Free | 10/min | 100/min | 20/min | 60/min |
| Pro | 60/min | 1000/min | 100/min | 300/min |
| Business | 200/min | 5000/min | 500/min | 1000/min |

**Rate Limit Key:** `ratelimit:<action>:user:<userId>` or `ratelimit:<action>:ip:<ip>`

**Fail-open:** If Redis is down, the middleware calls `next()` — rate limiting degrades gracefully.

---

### 4.4 Authentication Flow (LLD)

```
POST /api/auth/signup
  → validate email + password (min 8 chars)
  → check duplicate email (case-insensitive)
  → bcrypt.hash(password, 12) — 12 salt rounds
  → INSERT user (UUID primary key, plan_type='free')
  → generateTokens(user) — access + refresh JWT
  → Return tokens + user info

POST /api/auth/login
  → DB SELECT user by email (lowercased)
  → bcrypt.compare(password, hash)
  → generateTokens(user)
  → Tokens returned (stored in browser cookies + localStorage)

POST /api/auth/refresh
  → jwt.verify(refreshToken, JWT_REFRESH_SECRET)
  → Sign new accessToken with JWT_SECRET
  → Return { accessToken }

JWT Payload: { id, email, plan_type }
Access Token: 15 minutes
Refresh Token: 7 days
```

**Token extraction in middleware:**
1. Check `Authorization: Bearer <token>` header (for API clients)
2. Fallback to `req.cookies.access_token` (for browser)

**optionalAuth vs authenticate:**
- `authenticate` → **blocks** if no token. Used for protected routes.
- `optionalAuth` → **never blocks**, attaches user if token present. Used for redirects (to determine rate limit tier).

---

### 4.5 Analytics System (LLD)

**Why async analytics?**
The redirect latency budget is ~5ms. GeoIP lookup + DB insert would add ~20ms. So analytics are queued.

```
Click happens
  └── click_count++ (fast inline DB update)
  └── analyticsQueue.add('track-click', { urlId, ip, userAgent, referer })
  └── HTTP redirect (user gets URL immediately)

[Background — BullMQ Worker]
  └── Job picked up by analyticsWorker.js
  └── UAParser(userAgent) → { device, browser, os }
  └── geoip.lookup(ip) → { country, city }
  └── DB INSERT into analytics table
```

**Analytics queries use PostgreSQL date_trunc:**
```sql
SELECT date_trunc('day', created_at) as time_bucket,
       COUNT(*) as clicks,
       COUNT(DISTINCT ip_address) as unique_clicks
FROM analytics
WHERE url_id = ? AND created_at >= ?
GROUP BY time_bucket
ORDER BY time_bucket ASC;
```

---

## 5. 🗄️ Database Schema (LLD)

### `users` table
```
id                       UUID PRIMARY KEY (gen_random_uuid())
email                    VARCHAR(255) UNIQUE NOT NULL
password_hash            VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL
display_name             VARCHAR(100)
plan_type                ENUM('free', 'pro', 'business') DEFAULT 'free'
razorpay_customer_id     VARCHAR(100)
razorpay_subscription_id VARCHAR(100)
links_created_this_month INTEGER DEFAULT 0
billing_cycle_start      TIMESTAMP DEFAULT NOW()
created_at               TIMESTAMP
updated_at               TIMESTAMP
INDEX: email
```

**Why UUID for users?** Security — sequential integer IDs leak user count. UUIDs are unpredictable.

### `urls` table
```
id           BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY
short_code   VARCHAR(12) UNIQUE NOT NULL
long_url     TEXT NOT NULL
user_id      UUID REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE  -- nullable (anonymous)
custom_alias BOOLEAN DEFAULT FALSE
password_hash VARCHAR(255)                                 -- nullable
expires_at   TIMESTAMP                                     -- nullable
one_time     BOOLEAN DEFAULT FALSE
is_active    BOOLEAN DEFAULT TRUE
click_count  INTEGER DEFAULT 0
title        VARCHAR(255)
created_at   TIMESTAMP
updated_at   TIMESTAMP
INDEXES: short_code, user_id, created_at
```

### `analytics` table
```
id         BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY
url_id     BIGINT REFERENCES urls(id) ON DELETE CASCADE NOT NULL
ip_address INET                          -- PostgreSQL native IP type
country    VARCHAR(100)
city       VARCHAR(100)
device     VARCHAR(50)
browser    VARCHAR(50)
os         VARCHAR(50)
referer    TEXT
created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT NOW()
INDEXES: url_id, created_at, (url_id, created_at) composite
```

**Why `INET` type?** PostgreSQL's native IP type supports both IPv4 and IPv6.

**Why composite index `(url_id, created_at)`?** Analytics queries always filter by `url_id` first, then time range. Composite index serves both.

