## 11. 🔐 Security Measures

| Threat | Mitigation |
|---|---|
| Brute force login | Rate limiting (5/min unauthenticated) |
| XSS | Helmet security headers |
| Clickjacking | Helmet X-Frame-Options |
| Malicious URLs | URL validator + Redis blacklist |
| Re-shortening chains | Block known shortener domains |
| SQL injection | Knex parameterized queries |
| IDOR | All DB queries scope by `user_id` |
| Weak passwords | bcrypt with 12 salt rounds |
| JWT tampering | HMAC-signed JWT, verified on every request |
| Payment fraud | HMAC-SHA256 webhook signature verification |
| Username enumeration | Generic "Invalid email or password" message |
| Proxy bypass | `trust proxy` setting for real IP detection |

---

## 12. 📊 Performance Optimizations

| Optimization | Where | Why |
|---|---|---|
| Redis cache | URL redirect | Sub-ms lookup vs ~5ms DB query |
| Async analytics | BullMQ worker | Redirect not blocked by GeoIP + DB write |
| Gzip compression | All API responses | ~70% size reduction |
| DB indexes | short_code, user_id, (url_id, created_at) | Fast lookups |
| Connection pooling | Knex (min 2, max 20) | Reuse DB connections |
| click_count denorm | urls table | Dashboard stat without COUNT join |
| Promise.all | getUserLinks | Count + data queries run in parallel |
| Lua atomic ops | Rate limiter | Atomic Redis read-modify-write |

---

## 13. 🎯 Interview Questions & Answers

### System Design Questions

**Q1: Why did you use Redis for caching instead of in-memory (like a Map)?**
> In-memory cache is per-process and doesn't scale horizontally. If you run 3 Node.js instances behind a load balancer, each has its own Map — one might cache miss while others have data. Redis is a **shared external cache** visible to all instances. Also, Redis persists across server restarts.

**Q2: How does your URL shortening handle collisions?**
> I generate a 5-character code using `crypto.randomBytes(5)` mapped to Base62 charset. If it already exists in the DB, I loop and generate another. With 62^5 = ~916 million possible codes, collisions are rare. At scale, you'd use **pre-generated batches** or the **Snowflake + Base62** approach which is guaranteed unique without any DB check.

**Q3: What happens if Redis goes down?**
> The system degrades gracefully:
> - Rate limiter: **fail-open** (allow all requests, log error)
> - Short code redirect: falls back to PostgreSQL (cache miss path always works)
> - BullMQ: failsafe try/catch, analytics just won't queue
> The Redirect always works because PostgreSQL is the source of truth.

**Q4: How would you scale this to handle 100M URLs?**
> - **Horizontal scaling:** Multiple Node.js instances behind load balancer (shared Redis cache already works)
> - **DB sharding:** Shard urls table by `short_code` hash
> - **Read replicas:** Analytics queries (heavy reads) go to replicas
> - **CDN caching:** Cloudflare in front — cache 301 redirects at edge nodes
> - **Pre-computed short codes:** Generate codes in batches into a Redis pool, pop one when needed — eliminates the uniqueness check loop
> - **Separate analytics DB:** Move analytics to ClickHouse or TimescaleDB for better time-series performance

**Q5: Why not use MongoDB instead of PostgreSQL?**
> URLs + user data are **relational** — users OWN urls, analytics belong TO urls. PostgreSQL's foreign keys with `ON DELETE CASCADE` handle cleanup automatically. PostgreSQL also has `date_trunc`, `inet` type, and window functions used directly for analytics. MongoDB would require application-level joins and custom IP handling.

**Q6: Explain the Token Bucket algorithm and why you chose it over Fixed Window.**
> **Fixed Window:** Count requests in a 60-second window. Flaw: a user can make 2x their limit if they burst at the window boundary (59th second of window 1 + 1st second of window 2).
> **Token Bucket:** Tokens refill smoothly over time. You can burst up to max_tokens but then refill at max/interval rate. It handles bursty traffic gracefully — better user experience. Implemented atomically with a Lua script to prevent race conditions.

**Q7: Why did you use two Redis connections (one for app, one for BullMQ)?**
> BullMQ needs `maxRetriesPerRequest: null` and `enableReadyCheck: false` for its blocking list operations (`BRPOP`). Using the same connection would conflict with main app settings. Standard practice: one connection for app operations, one for BullMQ.

**Q8: How do you handle the ordering of Express routes to prevent conflicts?**
> Order: Static files → API routes → Named pages → Short code wildcard → 404 handler. If the wildcard was before named pages, `/dashboard` would be treated as a short code lookup. **Specificity first, wildcards last.**

---

### Security Questions

**Q9: Why do you use two JWT tokens (access + refresh)?**
> Access tokens are **short-lived (15 min)** to limit damage if stolen. Refresh tokens **(7 days)** let users get new access tokens silently without re-logging. Even if the access token is leaked via XSS, it expires in 15 minutes max.

**Q10: Explain the "user enumeration" prevention in your login.**
> Whether the email doesn't exist OR the password is wrong, I return the same message: `"Invalid email or password"`. If I returned `"Email not found"`, an attacker could enumerate valid email addresses.

**Q11: Why do you verify Razorpay webhook signatures?**
> Without signature verification, an attacker could send a fake POST to `/api/payments/webhook` claiming a payment completed, upgrading themselves to Pro for free. HMAC-SHA256 signature (using the webhook secret only Razorpay and I know) proves the event genuinely came from Razorpay.

**Q12: What is the `trust proxy` setting for?**
> Without it, `req.ip` behind a reverse proxy (Nginx, Cloudflare) would always be the proxy's IP, not the real user's IP. `app.set('trust proxy', 1)` tells Express to trust `X-Forwarded-For` header. Critical for rate limiting — otherwise you'd rate limit the proxy, blocking all users.

---

### Database Questions

**Q13: Why is `user_id` in the urls table nullable?**
> Anonymous users (not logged in) can still shorten URLs — it's a growth strategy (try before you sign up). `user_id = null` means anonymous. Plan limits only apply when `user_id` is present.

**Q14: Why do you have both `click_count` on urls AND detailed records in analytics?**
> **Denormalization for performance.** `click_count` is a fast integer for dashboard overview. The `analytics` table has per-click detail for granular reporting. Without this, every dashboard load would need a `COUNT(*)` on analytics — slow with millions of clicks.

**Q15: Why UUID for users but BIGSERIAL for URLs?**
> **Users:** UUID prevents sequential ID enumeration (security). Few users so UUID overhead is fine.
> **URLs:** Hot table with potentially billions of rows. BIGSERIAL is smaller (8 bytes vs 16 bytes), faster for index lookups, auto-incremented by DB.

**Q16: What is the composite index on (url_id, created_at) for?**
> Analytics queries always look like: `WHERE url_id = 42 AND created_at >= '2024-01-01'`. The composite index serves both conditions — DB narrows by `url_id` first (high selectivity), then by time range. Index order matters — equality field (`url_id`) first.

**Q17: What is `ON DELETE CASCADE` used for?**
> If a user is deleted, all their URLs are automatically deleted. If a URL is deleted, all its analytics records are automatically deleted. Maintains referential integrity at DB level without needing DELETE cascades in application code.

---

### JavaScript/Node.js Questions

**Q18: How do you handle errors globally?**
> `AppError` class extends `Error` with `statusCode` and `code` fields. All service functions throw `AppError`. The `errorHandler` middleware (registered last) catches all errors — if it's an `AppError`, uses the status code; otherwise returns 500. Centralizes error formatting.

**Q19: What's the difference between running the analytics worker in the same process vs separate?**
> In **development**, `analyticsWorker.js` is `require()`d in `server.js` — runs in same process, simpler setup. In **production**, run `npm run worker` in a separate process/container so it doesn't compete for resources with the web server and can be scaled independently.

**Q20: Why is `createBullConnection()` a factory function?**
> Each BullMQ Queue and Worker needs its own dedicated Redis connection. BullMQ's connection uses blocking operations. A factory creates a fresh `ioredis` instance each time. If you shared one connection, BullMQ's blocking operations would interfere with normal Redis commands.

---

### Architecture Questions

**Q21: What architectural pattern does this project follow?**
> **Layered MVC with Service Layer:**
> - Routes → entry point, apply middleware
> - Controllers → thin HTTP handlers, no business logic
> - Services → all business logic, DB, cache operations
> - Utils → pure stateless helper functions
> - Middleware → cross-cutting concerns
> Separation of concerns makes testing easier — test services independently without HTTP.

**Q22: How does the SaaS subscription model work end-to-end?**
> 1. User clicks "Upgrade to Pro" on pricing page
> 2. Frontend calls `POST /api/payments/subscribe`
> 3. Server calls Razorpay API: creates subscription object with plan ID
> 4. Razorpay subscription URL sent to frontend
> 5. User pays via Razorpay checkout
> 6. Razorpay fires `subscription.activated` webhook to our server
> 7. Webhook handler updates `users.plan_type = 'pro'` in DB
> 8. User now gets Pro rate limits and features

**Q23: How does plan enforcement work for custom aliases?**
> In `urlService.js`, `shortenUrl()` checks:
> ```javascript
> if (user && user.plan_type === 'free') {
>   throw new AppError('Custom aliases require a Pro or Business plan', 403);
> }
> ```
> The user's `plan_type` comes from the JWT payload (set at login). This is server-side — a client cannot bypass it.

**Q24: How do you prevent IDOR (Insecure Direct Object Reference) attacks?**
> Every DB query scopes by `user_id`:
> ```javascript
> db('urls').where({ id: linkId, user_id: userId })
> ```
> User A cannot access User B's links even if they know User B's link ID. Returns 404 (not 403) for unauthorized access — prevents confirming the resource exists.

**Q25: Why do you prevent shortening already-short URLs?**
> URL chains (short.ly → bit.ly → real URL) are used in phishing to hide destinations. Also makes analytics meaningless — you'd track clicks to the intermediate shortener. The `SHORTENER_DOMAINS` list in `urlValidator.js` blocks known shorteners.

---

### Behavioral Questions

**Q26: What was the hardest part of building this?**
> Getting the Express route order right. The wildcard redirect handler `/:shortCode` must come after all named routes. Early on, visiting `/dashboard` would trigger a short code lookup, find nothing, and return 404. Debugging middleware order in Express requires understanding top-to-bottom sequential processing.

**Q27: What would you improve with more time?**
> 1. **Pre-computed short code pool** in Redis for O(1) guaranteed-unique codes
> 2. **ClickHouse/TimescaleDB** for analytics (better time-series performance)
> 3. **Google OAuth** login (library `google-auth-library` already installed)
> 4. **Email verification** and password reset (nodemailer + otp-generator already installed)
> 5. **Custom domains** (users bring their own domain: `go.mycompany.com/link`)
> 6. **Unit tests** with Jest
> 7. **A/B testing** — split traffic between two long URLs

**Q28: Why did you install `nodemailer` and `otp-generator` if they're not used?**
> They were planned for email verification and OTP-based 2FA/password reset. The infrastructure is in place, but not implemented in this phase. Shows forward-thinking — adding email flows later won't require dependency changes.

---

## 14. ⚡ Quick-Fire Technical Facts

| Question | Answer |
|---|---|
| Short code length | 5 characters |
| Total possible short codes (5-char Base62) | 62^5 = ~916 million |
| Cache TTL | 1 hour (3600 seconds) |
| Access token lifetime | 15 minutes |
| Refresh token lifetime | 7 days |
| Free plan monthly limit | 100 links |
| bcrypt salt rounds (users) | 12 |
| bcrypt salt rounds (link passwords) | 10 |
| BullMQ retry attempts | 3 with exponential backoff |
| Analytics worker concurrency | 10 jobs in parallel |
| Redis maxmemory (docker) | 256 MB |
| Redis eviction policy | allkeys-lru |
| DB connection pool (prod) | min: 2, max: 20 |
| Snowflake epoch | 2026-01-01T00:00:00Z |
| Max machine IDs (Snowflake) | 1024 (2^10) |
| Max IDs per ms per machine (Snowflake) | 4096 (2^12) |
| URL max length | 2048 characters |
| Custom alias max length | 30 characters |
| Custom alias min length | 3 characters |
| Redirect type (regular links) | HTTP 301 Permanent |
| Redirect type (one-time links) | HTTP 302 Temporary |

---

## 15. 🧩 Design Patterns Used

| Pattern | Where | Why |
|---|---|---|
| **Service Layer** | `services/` | Separates business logic from HTTP handling |
| **Factory** | `createBullConnection()`, `createRateLimiter()` | Create configured instances on demand |
| **Middleware Chain** | Express pipeline | Composable, ordered request processing |
| **Token Bucket** | `rateLimiter.js` | Smooth rate limiting algorithm |
| **Write-Through Cache** | `urlService.js` | Cache updated on every write |
| **Observer** (event-driven) | BullMQ + Worker | Decouple analytics from redirect |
| **Webhook** | `paymentService.js` | Razorpay pushes payment events to server |
| **Facade** | Controllers | Thin wrapper over complex service logic |
| **Singleton** | `redis.js`, `database.js` | One shared DB/Redis connection per process |

---

## 16. 🏁 One-Line Project Summary (memorize this)

> "NanoURL is a **production-grade URL Shortener SaaS** built with **Node.js + Express + PostgreSQL + Redis + BullMQ**. It shortens URLs with unique 5-character codes, supports **custom aliases** (Pro plan), **password protection**, **expiration**, and **one-time links**. Redirects are served in ~2ms via Redis caching, and **click analytics** (country, device, browser) are processed **asynchronously** via a BullMQ worker to avoid blocking redirects. It has a **Token Bucket rate limiter** using Redis Lua scripts, **JWT authentication** with access + refresh tokens, and **Razorpay subscription billing** for monetization."
